### [Genesis Chapter 29](../../../bib/kjv/gen029.htm#001.md)

[Genesis 29:1](../../../bib/kjv/gen029.htm#001.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_001">gen 29:1</span></span>

and came into the land

Jacob at Haran becomes a sterling illustration, if not type, of the
nation descended from him in its present long dispersion. Like Israel,
he was:

\(1\) Out of the place of blessing ([Gen
26:3](../../../bib/kjv/gen026.htm#003).md).

\(2\) without an altar ([Hos 3:4](../../../bib/kjv/hos003.htm#004).md);
([Hos 3:5](../../../bib/kjv/hos003.htm#005).md).

\(3\) gained an evil name ([Gen 31:1](../../../bib/kjv/gen031.htm#001).md);
([Rom 2:17-24](../../../bib/kjv/rom002.htm#017).md).

\(4\) but was under the covenant care of Jehovah ([Gen
28:13](../../../bib/kjv/gen028.htm#013).md); ([Gen
28:14](../../../bib/kjv/gen028.htm#014).md); ([Rom
11:1](../../../bib/kjv/rom011.htm#001).md); ([Rom
11:25-30](../../../bib/kjv/rom011.htm#025).md).

\(5\) and was ultimately brought back ([Gen
31:3](../../../bib/kjv/gen031.htm#003).md); ([Gen
35:1-4](../../../bib/kjv/gen035.htm#001).md); ([Eze
37:21-23](../../../bib/kjv/eze037.htm#021).md).

The personal lesson is obvious: while Jacob is not forsaken, he is
permitted to reap the shame and sorrow of his self-chosen way.

